Water Use Data from Environment and Climate Change Canada

[https://www.ec.gc.ca/eaudouce-freshwater/default.asp?lang=En&amp;n=EFDA57C6-1](https://www.ec.gc.ca/eaudouce-freshwater/default.asp?lang=En&amp;n=EFDA57C6-1)

**What is this repository?**

Environment and Climate Change Canada is a bilingual, government-sponsored website with information about Canada&#39;s natural resources and climate change statistics and governmental regulations. This is a massive scope—within this larger site (see path:)

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

there is a repository of data about water use, in which are eight links to data sets about water quality and water mapping.

**What are its strengths?**

- Intuitive to navigate; there is just one main page (&quot;Online data&quot;) with links to each data set.
- ECCC is careful to disclaim that these data sets are not their property, and may change
- The data sets themselves are housed within the ECCC website, and those individual pages are laid out very nicely, with an introduction, publisher information, and a table (see below) containing the actual resources, with further information on the right-hand side bar. Easy to use.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

- After clicking &quot;access&quot; you are taken to a new page, which is also laid out very nicely, with an abstract, a link to metadata, and links to data sets.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

What are its weaknesses?

- This is not an in-depth repository. It is not highly organized or structured like an academic research site.
- You have to follow a series of four links before actually downloading a dataset, and I believe that there is some redundancy in the occurrences of links. For example, this is on the first page:

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)
and I found this after clicking through to an entirely different data set:

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

**What can we learn from this repository?**

- I love how easy to use this is for the lay person. The web page structure is unintimidating and each link is well-labeled and clear.
- I don&#39;t love that you have to fall down a link rabbit hole just to get to the actual data set.
- I&#39;m not sure how to have the clarity without having the never-ending story of links.
